This result shows s the total number of Stack Overflow questions asked each month. THE SQL query is https://data.stackexchange.com/stackoverflow/query/1926661#graph:
```
SELECT
DATEFROMPARTS(YEAR(CreationDate), MONTH(CreationDate), 1) AS [Month],
COUNT(*) AS [Questions]
FROM Posts
WHERE
PostTypeId = 1
GROUP BY
DATEFROMPARTS(YEAR(CreationDate), MONTH(CreationDate), 1)
ORDER BY
[Month] ASC
```

2026: The Year of SWE
Folks, listen up. 2026 is going to be the YEAR OF THE SWE. Software Engineers, the REAL builders, the ones who actually MAKE things work.
TREMENDOUS talent, believe me.
Everybody said Al was going to replace them.
TOTAL disaster prediction. Al was the BIGGEST SCAM. FAILED to deliver.
Look at the numbers: hundreds of billions spent on GPUs, power plants the size of cities, and what do we get? Models that plateaued HARD in 2025.
Benchmarks flatlining, diminishing returns on scaling, experts calling it the "Automation Plateau." No real reasoning breakthrough, just fancy autocomplete on steroids. Useful? Sure, as a COPILOT. Great for boilerplate, quick fixes, boosting productivity 20-30%. But replacement?
NO WAY.

Screenshot of Blind post

NO WAY. SWEs using Al are more powerful than those who don't, but the Al alone? Can't architect systems, debug complex edge cases, understand real business domains without constant human oversight.
And jobs? Demand for skilled SWEs is exploding again. Entry-level got hit, sure, but senior engineers, the ones who integrate Al properly?
Salaries through the roof. Companies realizing they need MORE humans to wrangle these tools, not fewer. The bubble talk is everywhere, valuations stretched, low ROl on genAl pilots, but the winners? The SWEs building the actual products.
2026: SWEs take back control. Al stays in the passenger seat. HUGE comeback. The best is yet to come.

Screenshot of Blind post

- February 4, 2026
On February 4, 2026, soon as the clock strikes 9:30 AM and the markets open, an "event" will begin. You won't see it coming at first, maybe a quiet dip in pre market futures, a few red arrows on the Magnificent Seven tickers. But by 10:30, the algorithms will wake up. They'll notice the overnight whispers from hyperscalers quietly trimming capex guidance, the subtle admissions that all those trillions poured into data centers aren't spitting out the god like ROI everyone promised.
NVIDIA first. Down 8% in the opening hour, then 15% as panic sells trigger stops. The chip king, the one that carried the entire S&P on its back through 2025, finally cracks under the weight of its own hype. No more "sold out for years" narratives, just empty warehouses of Blackwell chips that nobody needs because the Al models hit a wall. Training costs exploded, but outputs?
Still hallucinating, still mediocre at real work. The bubble's air starts hissing out.

Screenshot of Blind post

By noon, the VIX spikes to 50. Circuit breakers trip. Talking heads on CNBC scream "healthy correction" while their faces go pale. But we know better. This is the reckoning. The Al miracle was always a mirage: endless capex chasing vaporware profits, valuations priced for a future that arrives too slow, too broken.
They told us Al would add trillions to GDP.
Instead, it added trillions to debt and P/E ratios.
Power grids strained, electricity bills soared, and for what? Chatbots that write bad poetry and code that needs human babysitting.
February 4 isn't random. It's right after earnings season exposes the cracks, after the last batch of
"strong guidance" gets walked back, after the Fed hints no more rate cuts because inflation's sticky again from all those tariffs and energy demands.

Big cities will be a thing of the past in 2026. The positions of the big cities today are dictated by proximity to farm regions, mining regions and by the structure of land and water routes.
By 2026, it will be possible to locate a food factory or a factory for generating power anywhere. Travel will be chiefly by air.
Therefore, men will no longer ensure the noises and traffic jams and high rents of a London or New York, but will spread out more evenly over the earth in great numbers of smaller cities.
Community by Airplane
Many people will live in the open country, making a daily journey of 100 or 200 miles by airplane just as at present men live in the suburbs and drive eight or ten miles by auto to offices in the city.
Perfection of the helicopter will make it possible for these air-commuters to land easily upon the tops of office buildings.
--Evansville Press, 20 June 1926
